      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "```python\ndef findPaths(grid):\n    n, m = len(grid), len(grid[0])\n    dp = [0] * m\n    dp[0] = 1\n    for i in range(n):\n        row = []\n        for j in range(m):\n            if grid[i][j] == 0:\n                row.append(dp[j])\n            else:\n                row.append(0)\n        dp = row\n    return dp[-1]\n```\nThis solution uses only two rows to keep the memory footprint low. It iterates over each row of the grid, and for each cell, it checks if the cell is valid (i.e., `grid[i][j] == 0`). If it is, it appends the number of paths to the cell to the left to the current row. If it's not, it appends 0. After iterating over all rows, it returns the last element of the final row, which represents the number of paths from the start to the end.",
